Two men have been sentenced to death for their role in a violent attack in Northwest China’s Xinjiang Uyghur Autonomous Region. The attack in April left 21 people dead, including 15 community workers and police officers.
The verdict was handed down by the Intermediate People’s Court in Kashgar Prefecture. One of the suspects was convicted of murder, organizing and leading a terrorist group, and illegally manufacturing explosives. The other, for murder and participating in the terrorist group.
On April 23rd, three community workers found knives and suspicious individuals in a residence. They were seized by the suspects hiding in the house. Nine police officers and township community officials rushed to the scene to help. They died after the suspects locked them in the house and set fire to it. Four more police were killed in the continued attack. Six suspects were killed in the fight and eight were captured at the scene. 11 others were captured later.
